{{Japanese name|Imamichi}} {{Infobox person | name = Tomonobu Imamichi | image = Tomonobu Imamichi.jpg | alt = | caption = | birth_name = | birth_date = {{Birth date|1922|11|19}} | birth_place = [[Tokyo]] | death_date = {{Death date and age|2012|10|13|1922|11|19}} | death_place = | nationality = Japanese | other_names = | occupation = Philosopher | known_for = }}
{{nihongo|'''Tomonobu Imamichi'''|今道 友信|Imamichi Tomonobu}} (November 19, 1922 – October 13, 2012) was a [[Japanese philosopher]] who studied [[Chinese philosophy]].<ref name="Mainichi">{{cite news|url=http://mainichi.jp/select/news/20121017k0000m060019000c.html|script-title=ja:訃報:今道友信さん８９歳＝東大名誉教授エコエティカ提唱|date=16 October 2012|publisher=''[[Mainichi Shimbun]]''|language=Japanese|accessdate=17 October 2012|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20130112022432/http://mainichi.jp/select/news/20121017k0000m060019000c.html|archivedate=12 January 2013|df=}}</ref>
==Life== Imamichi taught in Europe (Paris and Germany) as well as in Japan (he was also emeritus professor of the [[University of Palermo]]). Beginning in 1979 he was the president of the ''[[Centre International pour l'Étude Comparée de Philosophie et d'Esthétique]]'' and after 1997 of the [[International Institute of Philosophy]]. In 1976 he founded the journal ''Aesthetics''.
He translated [[Aristotle]]'s ''[[Poetics (Aristotle)|Poetics]]'' into Japanese (in 1972) and has written numerous books in Japanese. Imamichi was a supporter of [[transculturation|communication between cultures]]. He characterizes [[Western philosophy]] as an attempt to achieve a God's eye view (''das in-dem-Gott-sein''; to be in the being of God) and [[Eastern philosophy]] as an attempt to be in the world (''das in-der-Welt-sein''). Imamichi sees in both stances two incomplete and complementary [[humanism]]s, and observes that since the publication of ''[[The Book of Tea]]'', some Western philosophers have adopted a more Eastern stance while other Eastern philosophers have attempted to reach the Absolute or the Eternal.
Tomonobu Imamichi was the father of guitarist and songwriter [[Tomotaka Imamichi]], pianist Nobuko Kawaguchi, biologist Yukiko Imamichi and psychologist Tomoaki Imamichi.
